{
  "text": "It is well known that UV light damages DNA. Alterations such as pyrimidine dimer formation, base destructions, breakage of sugar phosphate chains and interstrand DNA-DNA crosslinks have been reported (see Reference 15 for a review). However, from current protocols for the fluorescent detection of ethidium-DNA complexes after gel electrophoresis, the impression emerges that UV-induced DNA damage is usually of minor importance (2) . With a standard UV transilluminator fitted with UV-B tubes, only insignificant damage is assumed to accumulate in a period of minutes [CITATION_1] .",
  "citation_candidates": [
